===Noun===
'''Beigeist'''

# Sell out; conformist (with a heavy connotation of careerism), as in the color beige, as in ‘beigeocracy’, that being the color of Starbucks lattes and corporate conformity. 
#:''Colorful nonconformists frighten Beigeists.'' - [http://www.jewishworldreview.com/0505/jennings052605.php3 Marianne M. Jennings], Jewish World Review, May 26, 2005

It is a term coined by writer [http://en.wikipedia.com/wiki/Mark_Ames Mark Ames] and popularized in Ames' [http://www.nypress.com/16/35/news&columns/feature.cfm notorious attack on author Chuck Klosterman], to describe anyone of Manhattan LA media ilk or other forces of bourgeois/corporate mediocracy or conformity.

[http://www.gawker.com/news/diary/beigeism-013153.php According to Gawker], Beigeist is "hipster slang used to slap those who march in lockstep with “beige” corporate America. Starbucks is mentioned often, perhaps because lattes are beige, as are Gap Chinos."

Re: the request for verification, 1) [http://www.nypress.com/16/35/news&columns/feature.cfm here] is the word as used in the [http://nypress.com New York Press], a national alternative weekly, 2) [http://exile.ru/ames/ames66.html here] is the word as used in [http://exile.ru the eXile], a Moscow based English language alternative weekly ("Somewhere in the cruise-control synapses of McFaul's beigeist brain, he senses that his arrest and trial is a real possibility."), and 3) [http://www.gawker.com/news/diary/beigeism-013153.php here] is the word as defined by [http://gawker.com Gawker], a top media blog.